                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d932">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.61351/12–2244: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Braden</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-28T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >December 28, 1944—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>969. The interested agencies of this Government consider that since a proposal
                    has been submitted to the Cuban Commission and no official reply has been
                    received, we are not inclined to indicate any amendments in our proposal at the
                    present time. This refers to your telegram no. 1076, December 22.</p>
                <p>It may be mentioned, for your personal and confidential information, that sugar
                    prospects in the Philippines are not as favorable as shown by reports of several
                    months ago. Consequently we wish to provide for 1946 sugar in our purchase
                    agreement. We would prefer that, in making your reply to Seiglie, you not
                    mention this but only that we are disinclined to make any amendments in our
                    present proposal until a reply has been received from the Cubans. Upon
                    acceptance by them of the price of 3 cents, we should be quite prepared to
                    receive and consider a counter proposal involving our complete offer, and we
                    consider that this position can in no way be interpreted as putting pressure on
                    the Cuban Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
